1.body:
# Quick start

Welcome to Nedoto, the remote and real-time configuration service.

To get started in 5 minutes, follow these steps:

## Sign up

Sign up for a free account at [nedoto.com](https://app.nedoto.com).

## Configure your project

Create a new [project](https://app.nedoto.com/projects), [environment](https://app.nedoto.com/environments),
and [configuration](https://app.nedoto.com/configurations) in the Nedoto dashboard.

## Retrieve your configuration

Use one of the following methods to retrieve your configuration:

### Developer SDK

If you are a developer you can retrieve your configuration with different SDKs for PHP and Javascript or Typescript: take a look [here](/developers).

### cURL

If you want to retrieve your configuration with cURL, use the following command:

```bash
curl --location 'https://app.nedoto.com/api/get/<your configuration slug>' \
--header 'X-Api-Key: <your api key>'
```

### Nedoto-cli

We create a small CLI command to test the retrieval of your configuration.  
Go to [https://github.com/nedoto/nedoto-cli](https://github.com/nedoto/nedoto-cli) and clone the CLI command.

Enter the **nedoto-cli** directory and type:

```bash
$ bash nedoto-cli.bash
```
1.title: Quick start

12.body:
# cURL

The simplest and common way to test and retrieve the value of your configuration via API is to use the
command line with cURL.

## Request

The very simple script shown below demonstrates how to call Nedoto's APIs via HTTP to retrieve the value of your
configuration:

Replace `<your api key>` with your API key value and `<your configuration slug>` with the slug of your configuration.

```bash
curl --location 'https://app.nedoto.com/api/get/<your configuration slug>' \
--header 'X-Api-Key: <your api key>'
```

Replace `<your configuration slug>` with the slug of your [configuration](https://app.nedoto.com/configurations) and `<your api key>`
with the value of your [API key](https://app.nedoto.com/api-keys) associated with the same environment as the configuration.

{% info :bulb: Info %}

The project, environment, configuration, and API key must all be enabled in Nedoto; otherwise, you will receive an error if
even one of these is disabled.

{% end %}

## Response

This is an example of the response that the call above might return:

```JSON
{
  "configuration": {
    "data": {
      "slug": "banner-configuration",
      "type": "code",
      "value": "{\"configuration-slug\":\"configuration value defined in app.nedoto.com\"}",
      "created_at": "2024-04-21T20:25:30+00:00",
      "updated_at": "2024-04-21T20:25:30+00:00"
    }
  }
}
```

{% info :bulb: Info %}

In this example, the response contains a configurations of type `JSON`, and its value is a simple JSON.

{% end %}

# Environments

This section explain how to manage environments in [Nedoto.com](https://app.nedoto.com).

## Create a new environment

The first time you use Nedoto, you won't have any environment.

To create a new environment, click on the purple "New environment" button at the top right.

![Create the new environment](/assets/tutorials/environments/env-create.png)

In the environment creation form, fill in the mandatory fields identified by a red asterisk and press the button "Create,"
or "Create & create another" to create multiple environments without leaving the form.

![Fill mandatory fields](/assets/tutorials/environments/env-create-1.png)

If the project creation is successful, you will be redirected to the environments list with the "Created" notification.

![Project list](/assets/tutorials/environments/env-create-2.png)

## Edit the environment

To edit an environment, click on the pencil icon next to the environment name, and you will be redirected to the editing page.

## Delete the environment

To delete an environment, click on the red trash can icon. A notification will prompt you to confirm. By
pressing the red button, the environment will be deleted.

![Delete an environment](/assets/tutorials/environments/env-delete.png)

---

{% info Info %}
To prevent unpleasant surprises, you cannot delete an environment that contains active or inactive configurations or assets.
{% end %}

If you attempt to delete such environments, don't worry, nothing will happen, but instead, you will be shown a
notification as depicted in the image below.

![Cannot delete an environment](/assets/tutorials/environments/env-delete-1.png)

## Accessing configurations or assets

To quickly access your configurations or assets, click on the highlighted buttons in the screen below:

![Accessing configurations or assets](/assets/tutorials/environments/env-access-to-var-or-assets.png)
2.title: Environments

3.body:
# Assets

This section explain how to manage assets in [Nedoto.com](https://app.nedoto.com).

## Create a new asset

The first time you use Nedoto, you won't have any asset.

To create a new asset, click on the purple "New asset" button at the top right.

![Create the new asset](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-create.png)

In the asset creation form, fill in the mandatory fields identified by a red asterisk and press the button "Create,"
or "Create & create another" to create multiple assets without leaving the form.

To upload your assets you can drag&drop the file in the upload area or click on it and choose the file to upload.

{% info :bulb: Max file size %}

The maximum size for each assts you can upload is 1Mb.

Your total available space for you plan is shown as subheading of the creation form, or you can find it in directly in
your [dashboard](https://app.nedoto.com/).

{% end %}

{% info :bulb: Supported file types %}

At the moment we support only these file types to be uploaded:

```text
- text/csv
- application/msword
- application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document
- image/gif
- image/gif
- text/calendar
- image/jpeg
- application/json
- application/ld+json
- image/png
- image/webp
- application/pdf
- text/plain
- application/vnd.ms-excel
- application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet
- application/xml
- text/xml
- application/zip
- image/svg+xml
```

{% end %}

![Fill mandatory fields](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-create-1.png)

If the asset creation is successful, you will be redirected to the assets list with the "Created" notification.

![Assets list](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-create-2.png)

## Edit the asset

To edit an asset, click on the pencil icon next to the asset name, and you will be redirected to the editing page.

## Delete the asset

To delete an asset, click on the red trash can icon. A notification will prompt you to confirm. By pressing the red
button, the asset will be deleted.

![Delete an asset](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-delete.png)

## Copy the URL of you assets

After you have uploaded your assets, you can find the URL by clicking on the copy icon next to the URL label found on
each row of every asset.

{% info :bulb: Tip %}

You can copy the URL of your assets to reference them individually, or use them within a configuration of
type `string`, `code`,
or `HTML`.

{% end %}

![Copy the asset URL](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-copy-url.png)

## Copy your assets to another environment

Sometimes, when you define an asset in the development or staging environment, you need to copy it, for example, to the
production environment.

This is just an example of how the "Copy to another environment" feature works.  
This way, you don't need to manually create a new asset; instead, you can simply copy it to another environment with a
click.

Click on the highlighted button:

![Copy the asset to another environment](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-copy-to-env.png)

A modal will appear, prompting you to select the environment to which you want to copy your asset:

![Select the environment where to copy the asset](/assets/tutorials/assets/asset-copy-to-env-1.png)
3.title: Assets

4.body:
# Api keys

This section explain how to manage the api keys in [Nedoto.com](https://app.nedoto.com).

## Create a new api key

To create a new api key, click on the purple "New api key" button at the top right.

{% info :bulb: Info %}

Api keys are automatically created each time a new environment is created.

You can create as many API keys as you want.

{% end %}

![Create a new api key](/assets/tutorials/api-keys/api-key-create.png)

In the api key creation form, fill in the mandatory fields identified by a red asterisk and press the button "Create,"
or "Create & create another" to create multiple api keys without leaving the form.

![Fill mandatory fields](/assets/tutorials/api-keys/api-key-create-1.png)

If the project creation is successful, you will be redirected to the projects list with the "Created" notification.

![Api key list](/assets/tutorials/api-keys/api-key-create-2.png)

## Edit the api key

To edit an api key, click on the pencil icon next to the api key name, and you will be redirected to the editing page.

## Delete the api key

To delete an api key, click on the red trash can icon. A notification will prompt you to confirm. By pressing the red
button, the api key will be deleted.

{% warning :bulb: Info %}

You cannot delete API keys that are associated with an environment.

API keys are deleted when an environment is removed.

Disable your API keys when you no longer need to use them or to deny access.

{% end %}

![Delete an api key](/assets/tutorials/api-keys/api-key-delete.png)

## Copy the api key value

To copy the value of the API keys, click on the copy icon next to the value of the API key found on each row.

![Copy the api key value](/assets/tutorials/api-keys/api-key-copy-value.png)
4.title: Api keys

5.body:
# Dashboard

The Nedoto dashboard is where you find useful information regarding the usage of your account.

## Global search

Nedoto offers an intelligent feature called global search.

With global search, you can search across projects, environments, configurations, and assets in a single accessible point
throughout Nedoto.

![Global search](/assets/tutorials/dashboard/global-search.gif)

## API call left

This widget shows the total number of API calls that are still available to you.

{% info :bulb: Info %}

The number of API calls varies by subscription plan.

The image below shows the total number in the free plan.

{% end %}

![Api calls left widget](/assets/tutorials/dashboard/api-calls-left.png)

## Real-time push left

This widget displays the number of remaining real-time pushes for your configurations.

{% info :bulb: Info %}

Each subscription plan has a different number of available real-time pushes.

The image below shows the total number in the free plan.

{% end %}

![Api calls left widget](/assets/tutorials/dashboard/real-time-push-left.png)

## Disk space left

This widget shows the available space for your assets.

{% info :bulb: Info %}

Each subscription plan has a different amount of space available.

The image below shows the total amount in the free plan.

{% end %}

![Api calls left widget](/assets/tutorials/dashboard/disk-space-left.png)

## API calls this month

This line chart shows the distribution of the API calls for each day of the current month.

It's very useful for seeing the requests that your application, website, or other services make to Nedoto.

![Api calls left widget](/assets/tutorials/dashboard/api-calls-this-month.png)
5.title: Dashboard

# Configurations

This section explain how to manage configurations in [Nedoto.com](https://app.nedoto.com).

## Create a new configuration

The first time you use Nedoto, you won't have any configuration.

To create a new configuration, click on the purple "New configuration" button at the top right.

![Create a new configuration](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-create.png)

In the configuration creation form, fill in the mandatory fields identified by a red asterisk and press the button "Create,"
or "Create & create another" to create multiple configurations without leaving the form.

![Fill mandatory fields](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-create-1.png)

{% warning :bulb: configuration slug %}

The configuration slug is automatically generated starting from the configuration name and must be unique inside the same
environment, otherwise you will receive an error.

{% end %}

{% info :bulb: Configuration types %}

At the moment we support these configuration types:

```text
- string
- integer
- float
- boolean
- code (json, javascript, php, etc.)
- html
```
{% end %}

If the configuration creation is successful, you will be redirected to the environments list with the "Created" notification.

![Project list](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-create-2.png)

## Edit the configuration

To edit a configuration, click on the pencil icon next to the configuration name, and you will be redirected to the editing page.

## Delete the configuration

To delete a configuration, click on the red trash can icon. A notification will prompt you to confirm. By
pressing the red button, the configuration will be deleted.

![Delete an environment](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-delete.png)

## Configuration history

A configuration can be created and modified multiple times.
Sometimes errors can occur in this process, so in Nedoto, we've added a feature called "History" that allows you to view
a log of changes and restore them with a single click.

To view the history of changes to a configuration, click on the highlighted button in the image below:

![Configuration history](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-history.png)

Here's how the history screen of a configuration looks.  
As you can see on the left, old values are listed, and on the right, you'll find the newly set values.

By clicking the "Restore" button, you can revert to the old values shown on the left:

![Configuration history details](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-history-1.png)

## Copy configuration to another environment

Often, when you define a configuration in the development or staging environment, you need to copy it, for example, to the
production environment.

This is just an example of how the "Copy to another environment" feature works.  
This way, you don't need to manually create a new configuration; instead, you can simply copy it with a click.

Click on the highlighted button:

![Copy configuration to another environment](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-copy-to-env.png)

A modal will appear, prompting you to select the environment to which you want to copy the configuration:

![Select the environment where to copy the configuration](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-copy-to-env-1.png)

## Real-time push

A configuration can be retrieved with a simple API call, but sometimes you may need to **push in real-time** the value of
your configurations without the need for a deployment.

Some examples include:

- Disabling a feature in real-time without a new deployment
- Changing an image in real-time without a new deployment
- Injecting JavaScript code into a smartphone application in real-time without a new deployment
- Sending a notification to all connected users in real-time
- Etc.

To push the value of your configurations in real-time, click on the highlighted button:

![Real-time configuration push](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-real-time-push.png)

A modal will appear, and by clicking the "Submit" green button, you will send the value of this configuration to all your
connected
clients in real-time:

![Real-time configuration push](/assets/tutorials/variables/var-real-time-push-1.png)

You have to implement the client-side logic to receive the real-time pushed value or use one of Nedoto SDKs.

9.body:
# Main concepts

In this section you'll learn the main concepts in Nedoto.


## Projects

Projects are the starting point of Nedoto.  
A project represent your product, your application or your website. Give to the project your product name to be simply
identifiable.

A project can be enabled or disabled.  
Disabling a project will switch off all the environments, configurations and assets in it, so be careful when disabling a
project that is currently used in production because it can have a huge impact on your product.

## Environments

Use the environments to group your configurations or assets for different scenarios, usually a good practice is to have three
different environments like: development, staging, production - but you can create as many environment as you need with
of course the names you wish.

Each environment belongs to a project.

Like the projects an environment can be enabled or disabled and this will affect the delivery of your configuration and
assets - so pay attention when disabling an environment that is already in production.

## Configurations

Configurations are Nedoto's core.

With the configurations you can simply store a single string, JSON or even HTML and retrieve or push in real-time to your
application or website or where ever you need.
Each configuration has a unique name for each environment to avoid naming collision.

You can choose different type of configurations supported at the moment:

```text
- string
- integer
- float
- boolean
- code (js, php, etc. or even json)
- html
```

## Assets

With the assets you can store any kind of document or image you need, these `mime-types` are currently supported:

```text
- text/csv
- application/msword
- application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document
- image/gif
- image/gif
- text/calendar
- image/jpeg
- application/json
- application/ld+json
- image/png
- image/webp
- application/pdf
- text/plain
- application/vnd.ms-excel
- application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet
- application/xml
- text/xml
- application/zip
- image/svg+xml
```

You can choose to deliver your assets via a simple URL or reference them inside your configurations, for
example inside a JSON, code or even HTML.

## Api keys

Api keys are used to retrieve your configurations or assets from your code.
Api keys must be included in each request inside the `X-Api-Key` HTTP request key.

You can create as many api keys as you need for each environment to let different applications use the same configurations.
Each api key can be enabled or disabled independently to give you the opportunity to allow or disallow certain clients.
9.title: Main concepts
